ABSTRACT of PROPOSED RESEARCH for 98
A)"Statistical mechanics"
-Quantum Hall effect. We will continue the study of minimal W-infinity
model, with the hope to propose an experiment which can confirm their
predictions.
-Frustrated systems and q-oscillators. Study of the solution of the XY
model and the physics of frustrated systems and of the algebraic properties
of q-deformed algebras.
-Quantum diffusion in random media: what happens when there are long
range interactions described by band matrices (either sparse or full)?
We are willing to follow both perturbative approaches, extended numerical
simulations and approximate analytical techniques.
-We will continue our research on the scaling properties of  river networks
using our recently proposed stochastic differential equations.
We have already seen by numerical integration that the observed 
scaling laws are reproduced in a spectacular way.
A full analytical treatment is still lacking and we are working on it.
We are studying genetic networks which obey an optimization principle,
i.e. the minimun energy dissipation, and we are trying to show that under
rather general conditions, spanning trees emerge as the optimal network.
-Protein Folding and cooperative phenomena in heteropolymers. We have 
proposed variuos methods to design new proteins and till now we have 
checked their performance in comparison with previous proposed techniques 
in lattice and off lattice models where it was possible a rigorous test.  
Our methods seem to work rather nicely and a lot of work on real proteins 
has started in the last months.
-Spin glasses. We study this system with three different approaches, the 
first consists in constrained annealed approximations, the second in 
a Bethe-Peierls variational approach and the third in using
the Onsager transfer matrix method to find the exact solution of 
two-dimensional Ising models with strip disorder.
-Characterization of complexity of noisy systems and stochastic models 
in theoretical biology and theoretical finance.
-Equilibrium  properties of spin and discrete models, and dynamical 
properties of field models in non-equilibrium processes.
In particular, in the last years, we have studied the phase diagram of
three-dimensional spin models and discrete surface models by using 
variational (Cluster Variation Method) and Monte Carlo methods. 
This line of research may have interesting implications
for the study of critical properties in field models.
-Study of granular media by means of kinetic models.
We want to clarify the relation between the non-gaussian
velocity distribution and the clusterization, that we observe in the 
presence of inelastic collisions. Moreover, we are interested in
the appearence of very slow relaxation mechanism 
towards equilibrium in such materials.        
-Investigation of the glassy behavior in lattice models
with p-spin interactions. Study of the approach to equilibrium by
means of simulation and Ginzburg-Landau time dependent equation.
-Study of models of microcracks in heterogeneous materials 
by means of numerical simulation and mean field analysis.

B)"Dynamical systems"
- Analytical methods for the semiclassical regime of classically chaotic
quantum maps.
-Geometrization of Hamiltonian dynamics in the language of Riemannian 
differential geometry.Interesting applications of this approach are 
expected for disordered and frustrated systems as well as for lattice 
gauge models.
-Study of heat conduction in chains of nonlinear oscillators. The main aim
is the search for an explanation of the divergence of the conductivity
that we have recently found in numerical simulations. 
-Further development of the ``chronotopic'' approach for the description of
spatially extended chaotic systems. The next goal is the possibility to
attribute a meaning to the ``imaginary'' part of the Lyapunov exponents.
-Perturbation theory for classical nearly-integrable hamiltonian systems. 
Perturbation series are sometimes convergent (KAM theory) but 
often divergent (Nekhoroshev theorem and normal forms theory). 
The problem of the origin of this different behaviour is far from 
being understood. Recently new approaches, closer to standard diagrammatic 
methods in perturbative quantum field theory, have been proposed. We are 
presently active in exploiting the relation between the classical and 
quantum perturbation theories for solving some open problems in the 
theory of the transition to chaos in classical nonlinear 
Hamiltonian systems. Summability methods (Borel transform) which have 
since long been applied to perturbation theory in quantum mechanics 
are systematically used. 
-Geometrical approach to renormalisation. A numerical counterpart of 
this study is the frequency analysis method for studying the transition to 
chaotic behaviour in celestial mechanics and in particle accelerators.
-Relaxation properties of proper thermodynamic observables 
by inspection of their time correlation functions; transport properties
in 2-d and 3-d anharmonic lattices; growth phenomena originating from
confining potentials; phase transitions in non-equilibrium phenomena
like front propagation and cell dynamics.
-We will continue the study of localization of energy in nonlinear
chains, which has led to the introduction of the concept of ``chaotic
breather".
-We will continue the classification of invariant manifolds in the
Fermi-Pasta-Ulam Hamiltonian.
-We will study the dynamics and the Lyapunov instability in systems
with long-range interactions.
-Predictability problem for systems with
several characteristic times, in particular by introducing 
the concept of predictability time for variables that are averaged 
on temporal window or on finite space-regions. We shall also 
investigate the possibility to use the FINITE SIZE LYAPUNOV EXPONENT
(FSLE), that we recently introduced, for the analysis of experimental 
data and for the study of predictability in presence of an 
incertitude on the evolution laws.  
We are now studying systems with many degrees of freedom, that are 
composed of globally coupled maps under the influence of a common 
internal field; we intend to characterize their possible macroscopically 
chaotic behavior by means of the FSLE. With the locution  macroscopic  
chaos we indicate the irregular behavior of some global variables 
of the system, with typical times much longer than the characteristic 
time of the microscopic dynamics, as may be given by the inverse of 
the first Lyapunov exponent. 
-In the study of the diffusion properties in velocity fields with 
a space-time structure, we intend to generalize the multiscaling 
method to the case of non delta-correlated noise. This kind of 
problem is natural in astrophysics and in geophysics, when keeping 
into account the small scales effects by means of a 
markovian-gaussian process. We shall be faced with the problem of the
anomalous diffusion and of the mechanisms of synchronization 
(of a stochastic-resonance type) for the increasing of the diffusion 
coefficient, in correspondence of some special values of the 
parameters on which the field depends. When the diffusion coefficient 
does not gives enough information, it is necessary to face the 
problem by the methods of dynamical system theory (e.g. FSLE and 
markovian approximations).  
-It is our goal to develop a new class of simple models for turbulence, 
starting from the wavelet decomposition of the Navier-Stokes equations 
and then selecting those interactions that result to be important in the 
determination of the statistical properties of the turbulent flow. In 
this way it should be possible to check the generalized Kolmogorov 
hypothesis and the small scales modelization techniques.
We also address our investigations in the direct numerical simulations 
of partial differential equations that, at variance with the 
Navier-Stokes equations, present a direct energy cascade even in two
dimensions. An interesting example are the equations for the 
electro-magnetohydrodynamics turbulence, that displays a Kolmogorov
like scaling also in two dimensions.
-For the connection between the lagrangian and eulerian statistical 
properties, to avoid the numerical difficulties in the generation
of a velocity field with a wide inertial range, we shall face the 
problem from the syntetic-turbulence point of view: it will be 
required to quickly and efficiently generate multiaffine fields. 
-Statistical mechanics of hydrodinamical systems with constraints, 
in connection with the equivalence of the ensemble in non-equilibrium 
statistical mechanics, as proposed by G. Gallavotti.

